name: tpf-ds-notebooks
description: A suite of sample Jupyter notebooks demonstrating and documenting how to obtain operational and business insights with collected z/TPF system metrics using data science
description_good_justification: With these Jupyter notebooks, you can explore the capability and value of using data science to discover valuable insights on a z/TPF system. They provide an interactive educational platform by containing a mixture of embedded documentation and executable Python code that can be run on a Jupyter Notebook environment. Common open-source libraries are used to show that collected z/TPF system metrics can be treated the same as other data sources in your enterprise environment.
interact_justification:
License

This code pattern is licensed under the Apache License, Version 2. Separate third-party code objects invoked within this code pattern are licensed by their respective providers pursuant to their own separate licenses. Contributions are subject to the Developer Certificate of Origin, Version 1.1 and the Apache License, Version 2.

Apache License FAQ
contribution_justification: Projects on GitHub by default use issues and pull requests, as encouraged by documentation such as <https://guides.github.com/activities/contributing-to-open-source/>.
contribution_requirements_justification: Minimum Python and Jupyter Notebook code provided as a starter kit for users to fork and expand for their own usage. It is not expected for users to contribute to the base version.
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/IBM/tpf-ds-notebooks/blob/master/LICENSE>.
floss_license_justification: The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification:
Dependencies

A Jupyter Notebook environment that contains the following libraries:

    Python (v3.5 or later)
    NumPy (v1.9 or later)
    Matplotlib (v3.0 or later)
    pandas (v0.24 or later)
    Seaborn (v0.9 or later)

The Anaconda Python distribution (v2018.12 or later) is recommended for a bundled installation of Jupyter Notebook and the required Python libraries.
documentation_interface_justification: Embedded comments in the Jupyter Notebook gives step-by-step instructions on where the data should come from (IBM z/TPF operating system) and how the data is aggregated and analyzed by different library functions. The repository also provides sample data for the specific analysis performed on the notebook so users do not need to gather their own from their TPF system.

maintained_justification: While not actively being enhanced, the YAML file that defines the list of required software packages and their minimum versions so users can validate if their environment with more recent packages can run the notebook. In addition, a convenient MyBinder link is provided to automatically generate a temporarily Jupyter Notebook environment with the required software packages and other project files, without requiring any installation on local hardware.

There is documentation on how to report security issues in a safe way
https://github.com/knative/community/blob/main/SECURITY.md
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: We have not had any vulnerabilities
build_justification:
We use CICD process to build images and publish
https://github.com/knative/test-infra
All the software is available to reproduce the build using open source tools on a linux system
build_common_tools_justification:
Our common tools PROW, Github Actions, Go, Bash
https://github.com/knative/test-infra
build_floss_tools_justification:
We use FLOSS tools like Go, Bash, and Linux
https://github.com/knative/test-infra
test_justification:
We use opensource tools like PROW and Github Actions all CICD code is open
https://github.com/knative/test-infra
test_invocation_justification:
We use the standard golang test framework and e2e kubernetes 
https://github.com/knative/test-infra
test_policy_justification:
New functionality or any changes always need to come with testing enforce with code coverage
https://github.com/knative/serving/blob/main/.codecov.yaml
tests_are_added_justification:
The tests are located with the release of the code in the same repository any
https://github.com/knative/serving/tree/main/test
warnings_justification:
We use safe language Go and use a linter
Code quality and linting CICD Github Actions here https://github.com/knative/actions/tree/main/.github/workflows
warnings_fixed_justification:
Code quality and linting CICD Github Actions here https://github.com/knative/actions/tree/main/.github/workflows
PR doesn't get accepted until warnings are addressed
warnings_strict_justification:
We are doing our best to but as many codequality, linting and style on PR checks with Github Actions preventing the code to get in with problems
Code quality and linting CICD Github Actions here https://github.com/knative/actions/tree/main/.github/workflows
know_secure_design_justification:
Working groups leads have experience developing secure software
You can find them here https://github.com/knative/community/blob/main/working-groups/WORKING-GROUPS.md
know_common_errors_justification:
Working groups leads have experience developing secure software and are familiar with common kinds of errors that lead to vulnerabilities 
You can find them here https://github.com/knative/community/blob/main/working-groups/WORKING-GROUPS.md
delivery_mitm_justification: Uses kubernetes api that are https and authenticated
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat:
No medium or high severity vulnerabilities are present
https://github.com/knative/serving/security
vulnerabilities_critical_fixed_justifica:
We have a process to take critical vulnerabilities and address them rapidly
https://github.com/knative/community/blob/main/SECURITY.md
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j:
We use codeql in github actions
https://github.com/knative/actions/blob/main/.github/workflows/security.yaml
static_analysis_fixed_justification:
Pull Requests are blocked if they github actions detect security problems
https://github.com/knative/actions/blob/main/.github/workflows/security.yaml
static_analysis_often_justification:
The integration with github is running the code analysis on every new change on every branch
https://github.com/knative/actions/tree/main/.github/workflows
dynamic_analysis_justification:
We use small amount of fuzzing in the control plane, but we could do more now with new version of Go1.18
https://github.com/knative/eventing/blob/main/pkg/apis/messaging/v1/roundtrip_test.go
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: We don't do memory safe analysis currently
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: we don't do this type of scanning
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: we don't do this type of scanning
test_continuous_integration_justificatio:
There is CI using Github Actions and infra testing using Prow
https://github.com/knative/test-infra
discussion_justification:

- Mailing list  https://groups.google.com/g/knative-dev
- Feature Track process https://github.com/knative/community/blob/main/mechanics/FEATURE-TRACKS.md

name: asap
description: A modern cmake starter project for C++ with a complete build lifecycle, testing, dependency management, etc. Portable across Linux, OS X and Windows.
contribution_justification: Projects on GitHub by default use issues and pull requests, as encouraged by documentation such as <https://guides.github.com/activities/contributing-to-open-source/>.
contribution_requirements_justification:
https://github.com/abdes/asap 
Coding standards are enforced automatically with linter and code style rules
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/abdes/asap/blob/master/LICENSE>.
floss_license_justification: The BSD-3-Clause license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The BSD-3-Clause license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: Some documentation basics file contents found.
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_interim_justification: The project uses a separate branch for development (develop) from the release branch (master). Releases are prepared on the develop branch and then merged onto master for final release when they are stable.
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
release_notes_justification: Non-trivial release notes file in repository: <https://github.com/abdes/asap/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md>.
tests_are_added_justification: The project does not include c++ source code by itself. It does however include built-in unit testing framework (Google Test) and predefined build targets to automate testing during development and CI. All releases run the test targets automatically.
tests_documented_added_justification: The documentation describes how to add tests and run them. All tests are run automatically. Code coverage targets produce detailed reports for test coverage.
delivery_mitm_justification: The project does not provide any internet services. It does however use HTTPS for its web site.
delivery_unsigned_justification: The project provides its release artifacts checksums exclusively through HTTPS from GitHub.
static_analysis_justification: The project includes pre-defined build targets for running clangtidy static analyser and c++ linter on the project code.
dynamic_analysis_justification: The project has no c++ source code in it, but does include a build target for linting c++ code added by projects based on it.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: The project has no c++ source code in it, but does include a build target for linting c++ code and running Google sanitizers on code added by projects based on it.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: At the moment no build targets are defined for fuzzing.
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
hardened_site_justification: Found all required security hardening headers.
